INTRODUCTION.
тАФтАФтАФтАФтАФтАФ

It is a matter for extreme gratification for the Royal Family, for Travancore and also for the Department for the Publication of Oriental Manuscripts, Trivandrum, that a treatise on natya, composed by ┼Ъr─л B─Бlar─Бma Varma Maharaja, in the midst of his arduous State duties, is now placed before the public. The work, based as it is on numerous previous authorities, is, in the main, the result of the practical experience of the author on Natya. This publication is therefore all the more important for those interested in the revival of Indian national dance, and especially for the student of Kerala theatre. The science of n─Бtya is defined by the author as рднрд╛рд╡рд░рд╕рд╛рд░реНрдердХреНрд░рд┐рдпрд╛рдХрд╛рд░рд┐рддреНрд╡рдВ рднрд░рддрддреНрд╡рдореН’ and this definition has been applied to the abhinayas of the various parts of the body, such as anga (head, &c.), up─Бс╣Еga (eye, &c.) and pratyaс╣Еga (neck, &c). Accepting r─Бga, t─Бla and other musical accompaniments as the external means of expressing emotions, the author deals in great detail with the various internal and external gestures, giving definitions and applications to one and all of them. Numerous systems of abhinayas, both internal and external, that had been in vogue in Kerala alone, have also been illustrated, and this is evident from the following lines found at the close of the different sub-sections of the book.

“рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрд╛рд▓рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЗ рдореБрджрд╛ред
рдкрд░рд╛рд╡реГрддреНрддрд╢рд┐рд░реЛ рдирд╛рдЯреНрдпреЗ рдЪреИрддреЗрд╖реБ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреБрдЬреНрдпрддреЗрее” (p. 25)

“рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрд╛рд▓рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЗ рдореБрджрд╛ред
рдПрд╡рдорд╛рджрд┐рд╡рд┐рд╢реЗрд╖реЗрд╖реБ рд╢рд┐рдЦрд░реЛ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреБрдЬреНрдпрддреЗрее” (p. 51 )

“рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрд╛рд▓рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЗрд╖реБ рдЪред
рдПрддреЗрд╖реНрд╡реЗрд╡ рд╣рд┐ рдХрд╛рд░реНрдпреЗрд╖реБ рд╡рдХреНрд░рдЧреЛ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреБрдЬреНрдпрддреЗрее” (p. 107)

“рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрд╛рд▓рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЗ рдореБрджрд╛ред
рд░рд╕рдирд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЛ рдирд╛рдЯреНрдпреЗрдЪреИрддреЗрд╖реБ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреБрдЬреНрдпрддреЗрее” (p. 191 )

“рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрд╛рд▓рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпреЗ рдореБрджрд╛ред
рдПрддреЗрд╖реНрд╡реЗрд╡ рд╣рд┐ рдХрд╛рд░реНрдпреЗрд╖реБ рдЪрд╛рдХреГрд╖реНрдЯрд╛ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреБрдЬреНрдпрддреЗрее” (p. 263)

Of course, the author treads on the path of the famous n─Бtya ┼Ы─Бstra of Bharata, but his teachings are the outcome of his practical experience and he may therefore be regarded as a higher authority on the subject of n─Бtya as is plain from the following lines:тАУ

“рджрдХреНрд╖рд┐рдгреЗ рд╡рд╛рдорд╕реВрдЪреА рдЪ рд╡рд╛рдореЗ рджрдХреНрд╖рд┐рдгрд╕реВрдЪрд┐рдХрд╛ред
рдкрджрд╡реНрдпрддреНрдпрд╛рд╕рднрд╛рд╡реЗрди рдкреБрд░рддрдГ рдкреГрд╖реНрдарддрдГ рд╕реНрдерд┐рддрд╛рее
рд╕реВрдЪреА рд╕реИрд╡ рд╡рд┐рдкрд░реНрдпрд╛рд╕рд╛ рдХреАрд░реНрддреНрддрд┐рддрд╛ рднрд░рддрд╛рдЧрдореЗред” (p. 262)

This precious work is incomplete as some folios at the end of the manuscript are not available, and as all my attempts to procure a complete copy have been in vain. I venture to think that the work was left incomplete like Citramim─Бms─Б, Rasagaс╣Еg─Бdhara and other productions.

The system of n─Бtya dealt with in this work, though based on previous authorities, is found to have been transfused by the practical knowledge of the author; and even an indifferent reader of the work cannot but be impressed by the wonderful mastery that the author had on the subject. From the following stanza,

“рдиреГрдкрдХреБрд▓рддрд┐рд▓рдХрдГ рд╢реНрд░реАрддрд╛рд▓рдорд╛рд▓рд╛рд╡рд┐рднреВрд╖рд╛тАУ

рдкрд░рд┐рдХрд▓рд┐рддрдирд┐рдЬрд╢реНрд░реАрдХрд╛рдиреНрддрд┐рд╕рдореНрдкреВрд░реНрдгрдЧрд╛рддреНрд░рдГред

рд░рд╕рд┐рдХрдЬрдирд╕рд╣рд╕реНрд░реИрдГ рд╢реЛрднрд┐рддрд╛рдпрд╛рдВ рд╕рднрд╛рдпрд╛рдВ

рднрд░рддрдорд┐рд╣ рд╡рд┐рдзрд╛рддреБрдВ рдкреНрд░рд╛рд░реНрдерд┐рддреЛ рд╡рдЮреНрдЪрд┐рд░рд╛рдЬрдГрее” (p. 6)

it can be inferred that the work was composed when the author, adorned with various accompaniments of dancing was seated amidst an assembly of numerous connoisseurs of the art. This also corroborates the statement that the definitions and applications of gestures explained herein are the result of his practical experience of the science. It appears that the royal author who had mastered the previous works on the subject has supplemented the science of n─Бtya with other systems current in Malabar; and in support of this statement can be quoted the following extract showing the views of Kohala on samyuta hasta and its amplification by our author,

рдорд╣реЗрд╢рдЧреБрд░реБрдкреВрдЬрд╛рдпрд╛рдордпрдВ рд╕реНрдпрд╛рджрднрд┐рд╡рд╛рджрдиреЗреетАЭ

рдкреНрд░рдХреГрддреЗ рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдорднрд░рддреЗтАУ

……. ……. ……. …… (p. 75)

The author thus expanding the system of n─Бtya of Bharata with other systems current in Malabar appears to be an incarnation of Bharata, Kohala and other hoary sages.

The work bears the significant title B─Бlar─Бmabharata as it was composed by Balarama, as may be seen from the following sloka found at the outset of the work:тАУ

“рддрддреНрд╕рд╛рд░рд╕рдЩреНрдЧреНрд░рд╣рдВ рдХреГрддреНрд╡рд╛ рдмрд╛рд▓рд░рд╛рдордорд╣реАрдкрддрд┐рдГред
рд▓реЛрдХрд╛рдирд╛рдореБрдкрдХрд╛рд░рд╛рдп рдХреГрддрд╡рд╛рдиреН рднрд░рддрдВ рдореБрджрд╛рее” (p. 12)

The prefix тАЬB─Бla" in B─Бlar─Бma, the name of the author, is a hereditary title manifesting submission to God ┼Ъri Padman─Бbha, the tutelary deity of the Travancore Royal House, in whom the ruling power of the State is vested. This has been fully dealt with in my introduction to B─Бlam─Бrt─Бndavijaya.

The author is known to have lived between 899тАУ973 M. E., corresponding to 1724тАУ1798 A. D., having been a ruling sovereign for the major portion of his life. Having mastered numerous arts and sciences even as a boy, he was a votary of the poetic muse and an equally intrepid soldier in battle. When he was about to start for waging war against the king of the country called “M─Бpr─Бna”, he is said to have sent the following message which took a poetic garb:

“рдорд╛рдкреНрд░рд╛рдгрдВ рддреНрдпрдЬ рдорд╛ рдкреНрд░рд╛рдгрдВ рдорд╛рдкреНрд░рд╛рдгрд╕рдорд╡рд▓реНрд▓рдн!ред
рдорд╛рдирд╡рд┐рдХреНрд░рдорддреЗрдЬреЛрднрд┐рд░реНрдорд╛рдирд╡рд┐рдХреНрд░рдорднреВрдкрддреЗ!рее”

This incident told about the author shows that poetry was a zealous mistress with him even when he was bent on quelling the pride of a powerful enemy. Many similar anecdotes have gathered around the name of this gifted author enshrining him in a halo of glory. In the introductory verse тАШрдЗрддреНрдердВ рд╣рд┐ рд░рд╛рдорд╡рдЪрдитАЩ (p. 4) the author claims descent from the great Solar race.

A life sketch of the author by Rao Sahib Mah─БkaviKavitilaka, Ullur S. Paramesvara Ayyar, M. A., B. L., a life, long student of Kerala antiquities, runs as follows:

“Maharaja Bala Rama Varma, the author of B─Бlar─Бmabharata, was one of the greatest and most distinguished sovereigns of Travancore. He was born on the 5th Karkatakam, 899 M. E. (1724 A. D.) The star of his nativity being Krttik─Б, he is popularly known as K─Бrtika Tirun─Бl. His father was Kerala Varma Koil Tampur─Бn of Kilim─Бn┼лr and mother R─Бni P─Бrvati B─Бyi. Maharaja B─Бla M─Бrt─Бnda Varma, the maker of modern Travancore, who ruled from 904 to 933 M. E. (1729тАФ1758) was his maternaluncle.

Quite early in life, Rama Varma gave remarkable proofs of his versatile genius, and under the fostering care of his uncle, became both an able soldier and an erudite scholar. He attained proficiency in many languages, and particularly in Sanskrit, Persian, Hindustani and Malayalam. Later, he employed Pietro de Vegas, a Portuguese teacher and studied both Portuguese and English under him. He is also known to have possessed a working knowledge of Dutch. He evinced extraordinary talents not only in literature, but also in music, dancing and kindred arts.

Rama Varma assisted his uncle in all the wars undertaken by him, and especially those against the Netherland East India Company, and the Rajas of Kayankulam, Ampalappuzha, Tekkumkur, and Vadakkumkur. When Ampalappuzha succumbed, so absorbing was his interest in culture that he collected all the ancient palm-leaf manuscripts preserved in the palace of the vanquished Raja and brought them over to the capital, leaving Ramayyan Dalawa, the famous minister and generalissimo of M─Бrt─Бnda Varma, to take charge of the trophies of war. Several of these manuscripts may even now be seen in the Trivandrum Palace Library. In the drama B─Бlamart─Бndavijaya, composed by the poet Devaraja of ─А┼Ыr─Бmam in South Travancore, in commemoration of the dedication by M─Бrt─Бnda Varma of his kingdom to ┼Ъr─л Padman─Бbha, his tutelary deity, on the 5th Makaram 925 M. E. (1750 A. D.), there are many passages revealing the great regard which the King had for R─Бma Varma, as a poet and patron of letters. The following description of R─Бni P─Бrvati B─Бyi, occurring in Act IV of that work is worthy of perusal :

The king, on hearing these words from the mouth of one of his attendants, says to himself as followsтАУ

** “рдЕрд╕реНрдорддреНрдкреНрд░реЗрдореИрдХрднрд╛рдЬрдирд╕реНрдп рд░рдордгреАрдпрдЧреБрдгрдЧрдгрд╛рдХрд░рд╕реНрдп рдорджреАрдпрдХреБрд▓рдирдиреНрджрдирд╕реНрдп рд╡рддреНрд╕рд╢реНрд░реАрд░рд╛рдорд╡рд░реНрдордгрдГ рдЕрдзреНрд╡рд░рд╛рдирд▓рд╕реНрдпрд╛рд░рдгрд┐рд░рд┐рд╡рд╛рд╡рд┐рд░реНрднрд╛рд╡рд╣реЗрддреБрд░рд┐рдпрдорднрд╡рддреНред рдЕрдиреЗрдирд╛рдкрд┐ рд╣реЗрддреБрдирд╛ рдирд┐рддрд╛рдиреНрддрдкреНрд░реЗрдорд╛рд╕реНрдкрджрдорд┐рдпрдорд╛рд╕реНрддреЗред” (p. 55.)**

The king’s high estimate of R─Бma Varma may be gathered from the following verse put into his mouth by the poet:

“рдЖрдЪрд╛рд░реИрдХрд╛рдирд┐рдзрд┐рдГ рд╕рдорд╕реНрддрдЬрдЧрддрд╛рдорд╛рдирдиреНрджрд╡рд╛рд░рд╛рдВрдирд┐рдзрд┐тАУ

рд░реНрджрд╛рддреДрдгрд╛рдордкрд┐ рдЪрд╛рдЧреНрд░рдгреАрд░реНрдордо рдХреБрд▓рд╛рдореНрднреЛрдзреЗрд░рдпрдВ рдЪрдиреНрджреНрд░рдорд╛рдГред

рдПрдирдВ рд╕рдиреНрддрддрдорд╛рд╡рд┐рд╢рдиреНрддрд┐ рд╡рд┐рджреБрд╖рд╛рдВ рд╕рдореНрдкрд░реНрдХрдЬрд╛рдГ рд╕рджреНрдЧреБрдгрд╛

рдорджреНрд╡рддреНрд╕рдВ рдЧрд┐рд░рд┐рд╕рдореНрднрд╡рд╛ рдЗрд╡ рдорд╣рд╛рдкрд╛рдереЛрдзрд┐рдордореНрднреЛрднрд░рд╛рдГрее

To make his own assurance on the point doubly sure, the king asks the pandits and poets assembled on the occasion whether his nephew knows anything of the various arts that he has learnt (рдорджреНрд╡рддреНрд╕реЛрд╜рдпрдорднреНрдпрд╕реНрддрд╛рд╕реБ рдХрд▓рд╛рд╕реБ рдХрд┐рдЮреНрдЪрд┐рджрдкрд┐ рдЬрд╛рдирд╛рддрд┐?) and they reply with one voice:

тАЬрдХрд▓рд╛рд╡рд╛рдиреН рд░рд╛рдордЪрдиреНрджреНрд░реЛрд╜рдпрдордХрд▓рдЩреНрдХрд╛рджреНрднреБрддреЛрджрдпрдГред

рддрддреНрддрддреНрдХрд▓рд╛рд╕реБ рдорд░реНрдорд╛рдгрд┐ рдзреАрдорддрд╛ рд░рд╛рдорд╡рд░реНрдордгрд╛ред
рдЕрдирд╛рдХреНрд░рд╛рдиреНрддрд╛рдирд┐ рд▓рдХреНрд╖реНрдпрдиреНрддреЗ рдирд╛рд╕реНрдорд╛рднрд┐рд░реНрдпрддреНрдирдорд╛рд╕реНрдерд┐рддреИрдГреетАЭ (p. 93)

It is needless to cite more references. Devaraja was a lifeтАУlong friend and courtтАУpoet of R─Бma Varma, and I am of the view that a veiled allusion to him is contained in the verse occurring in the introductory part of B─Бlar─Бmabharata:

“рдЕрдЦрд┐рд▓рдЧреБрдгрдирд┐рдзреАрдирд╛рдорд╛рд╢реНрд░рдпреЛ рджреЗрд╡рд░рд╛рдЬтАУ
рдкреНрд░рднреБрдЦрд╕рдХрд▓рджрд┐рдХреНрдкрд╛рд▓реЛрдкрдЧреАрддрд╕реНрд╡рдХреАрд░реНрддрд┐рдГред
рдмрд╣реБрдХрд╡рд┐рдЬрдирд╕рдореНрдорд╛рдирд╛рднрд┐рдирдиреНрджреНрдпрд╛рддреНрдордореВрд░реНрддрд┐тАУ
рд░реНрд╡рд┐рд▓рд╕рддрд┐ рдЪрд┐рд░рдЬреАрд╡реА рд╡рдЮреНрдЪрд┐рднреВрджреЗрд╡рд░рд╛рдЬрдГрее”

On the death of M─Бrt─Бnda Varma on the 27th Mithunam 933 (July 1758), R─Бma Varma ascended the throne, and reigned for a period of about forty eventful years. His death occurred on the 7th Mithunam 973 M. E. (July 1798). It is not possible here to attempt even a brief resume of his political and administrative career. Suffice it to say that he drove the Zamorin of Malabar from Cochin and compelled him to sue for peace, made Cochin surrender the taluks of Kunnattunad, Alangad, Parur and Shertallay, the Rajas of Alangad and Parur signing separate deeds of renunciation, entered into perpetual alliance with the Nawab of Arcot, relinquishing his transтАУghatian possessions, but securing for Travancore the taluk of Shencotta and the sacred temple of Cape Comorin without further molestation from the Nawab, erected the celebrated Nedumkotta fortifications on the northern frontier, purchased the ports of Cranganore and Ayikkotta from the Dutch as a means of further protection against enemies from that quarter, defeated Tippu Sultan of Mysore, consolidated the whole territory from Tovala to the Parur and executed a treaty of perpetual friendship and alliance with the English East India Company. The extent of Travancore to-day is practically the same as when he died in 1798 A. D. Maharaja R─Бma Varma was deeply religiousminded. He performed the Tul─Бpuru┼Яad─Бna in 935, Hiraс╣Зyagarbhad─Бna in 936, Br─Бhm─Бс╣Зс╕Нakaс╣нahad─Бna and Kalpavс╣Ыkс╣гad─Бna in 938 and Gosahasrad─Бna, Svarс╣Зak─Бmadhenud─Бna, Hiraс╣Зy─Б┼Ыvad─Бna, Hiraс╣Зy─Б┼Ыvarathad─Бna, Bh┼лmid─Бna, Viс╣гacakrad─Бna, Kalpakalat─Бd─Бna, Hemahastirathad─Бna, Pancal─Бngalad─Бna, Saptas─Бgarad─Бna, Manidhenud─Бna and Mah─Бbhutakatahad─Бna in 340 M. E., thus completing the sixteen Mah─Бd─Бnas or great gifts ordained by the Hindu religion. On the 23rd Mithunam 941 M. E. (1766) he made, following in the wake of his uncle, a dedication to ┼Ъr─л Padman─Бbha, of the territories surrendered by Cochin to Travancore. In 945 M. E. (1769), he purchased from the Raja of Ramnad the estate of Kakur in the Ramnad District for the performance of certain services in the Ramesvaram Temple. On his mother’s death on the 30th Edavam 957 M. E. (1782), he resolved to proceed on a pilgrimage to Ramesvaram and perform certain religious rites there for her merit. This resolution was carried out in Vrischikam 959 M. E. (1783). In 963 M. E. (1788), be got a y─Бga (Vedic sacrifice) performed on a grand scale at Alwaye on the northern kank of the Periyar river.

Neither Hyder Ali nor Tippu Sultan was able to devastate Travancore, as they did the other parts of Keral.When Tippu Sultan carried fire and sword into Malabar, innumerable Hindus, high and low, fled to Travancore for shelter, and the Maharaja, true to the traditions of his family, protected every one of them, as befitted his status, the question of cost or consequential risk never for once entering into his calculation. Two Sanskrit verses portraying the general panic which Tippu’s invasion created in Malabar have come down to us and they are worthy of quotation here:

“рддреБрд░реБрд╖реНрдХреЛ рдирд┐рд╖реНрдХреНрд░рд╛рдорддреНрддреБрд░рдЧрд╕реНрд╡реБрд░рдХреБрджреНрджрд╛рд▓рджрд▓рд┐рддтАУ
рдХреНрд╖рдорд╛рдзреВрд▓реАрдкрд╛рд▓реАрдЪреБрд▓реБрдХрд┐рддрдЪрддреБрд╕реНрд╕рд┐рдиреНрдзреБрд╕рд▓рд┐рд▓рдГред
рд╣рдард╛рдХреГрд╖реНрдЯрддреНрд░реБрдареНрдпрддреНрдкреНрд░рддрд┐рднрдЯрд╡рдзреВрдЯреАрдкрд░рд┐рд╡реГрддрдГ
рдкреНрд░рддрд╕реНрдереЗ рдХрд╛рд░реНрддрд╛рдиреНрддреАрдВ рдХрдХреБрднрдорд┐рддрд┐ рд╡рд╛рд░реНрддрд╛ рд╕рдордЬрдирд┐рее

рдЬрд┐рддреНрд╡рд╛ рд╣рд▓реНрд▓реЛрд╣рд▓реЗрд╢рдВ рдпрд╡рдирд╡рд░рдпреБрддрдГ рдХреЛрд▓рднреВрдкрд╛рд▓рдореМрд▓рд┐рдВ
рд╣реГрддреНрд╡рд╛рд░реНрдерд╛рдиреЗрддрджреАрдпрд╛рдирдкрд┐ рдкреБрд░рд▓рд┐рдкрддрд┐рдВ рд╢реИрд▓рдкрд╛рдереЛрдзрд┐рдирд╛рдердореН ред
рдзрд┐рдХреНрдХреБрд░реНрд╡рдиреН рдорд╛рдЯрднреВрдкрдВ рд╕рджрд╕рд┐ рдирд┐рдЬрднрдЯреИрдГ рд╕рд╛рдХрдорд╛рд╕реНрддреЗ рддреБрд░реБрд╖реНрдХрдГ
рдХрд╛рд░реНрддрд╛рдиреНрддреАрдВ рдЧрдиреНрддреБрдХрд╛рдореЛ рджрд┐рд╢рдордЦрд┐рд▓рдЬрдирд╛рдиреН рдкрд╛рд╣рд┐ рд╡рдЮреНрдЪрд┐рдХреНрд╖рд┐рддреАрд╢!рее”

The asylum accorded by the Mahraja to those refugees was one of the several reasons advanced by the Sultan for invading Travancore. His first attempt, however, failed miserably. Even the Muhammadan historian Mir Husain Ali Khan Kirmani, admits that, on the 28th December 1789, “the enemy attacked the Sultan’s troops on all sides with arrows and musketry and caused incalculable distress and confusion among them…………Three or four hundred horsemen, men of good families, gave substantial rpoofs of their valour and were all killed and wounded in front of the Sultan………..In short the Sultan and Kamruddin Khan escaped out of the whirlpool of their misfortunes, and the rest of the Khans……….were never after heard of”. When Tippu, maimed for life in that ambush, came again to wreak his vengeance on the Maharaja, the Periyar river, which was in high flood, arrested his advance, illustrating the truth of the observation made in the drama.Pratij├▒─Бyaugandh─Бrayaс╣Зa, attributed to Bh─Бsa.

“рдкрд░рдЪрдХреНрд░реИрд░рдирд╛рдХреНрд░рд╛рдиреНрддрд╛ рдзрд░реНрдорд╕рдЩреНрдХрд░рд╡рд░реНрдЬрд┐рддрд╛ред
рднреВрдорд┐рд░реНрднрд░реНрддрд╛рд░рдорд╛рдкрдиреНрдирдВ рд░рдХреНрд╖рд┐рддрд╛ рдкрд░рд┐рд░рдХреНрд╖рддрд┐рее”

and before the flood subsided, Lord Cornwallis was virtually at the gate of Seringapatam. R─Бma Varma was loyally served by very able ministers, the foremost among whom were R─Бja Ke┼Ыava D─Бs, Aiyappan M─Бrt─Бс╣Зс╕Нan Pillai and Mah─Бdevayyan Subbayyan, as also his distinguished Flemish general, Eustatius de Lannoy who died in 1777 A. D. On the 2nd July 1774, Pope Clement XIV sent him a message of goodтАУwill, in recognition of the kindness and consideration shown by him to his Christian subjects. On the 10th October 1790, the Maharaja was honoured by the Nizam of Hyderabad, in his capacity as the vicegerent of the Muhammadan Emperor of Delhi in South India, with the titles of K─лс╣Ыiс╣нapati Manne Sultan Maharaja Raja Raina Raja Bahadur Shamsher Jung, and these titles are even now borne by his successors.

The charities of the Maharaja were so liberal and widespread that he came to be known as Dharmar─Бja throughout India. Contemporary writers have left glowing accounts of his high character. Fra Paolino da San Bartolomeo, the Carmelite friar and scholar who lived for several years in Travancore and who knew the Maharaja intimately, has recorded: “He is an affable, polite, contented, prudent, friendly man……….For my part I could not help admiring the goodness of heart, the affability and humanity of this prince as well as the simplicity of his household establishment and way of life”. He has further stated: “Public security is again restoredthroughout the whole country; robbery and murder are no longer heard of; no one has occision to be afraid on high ways; religious worship is never interrupted; and people may rest assured that on every occasion justice will be speedily administered”. Adriran Moens, the Dutch Governor of Cochin, has observed that he “directs the principal affairs himself, enquires into, and is acquainted with every thing that is of any importance”. The English Commissioners appointed to settle the affairs of Malabar in 1792 A. D., have remarked: “We own he left a very favourable impression on our minds both as to his personal qualities and what we consider as the unequivocal sincerity of his attachment to he Honourable Company”.

The Maharaja was a great lover of culture. When Fra Paolino told him that he had studied Amarako┼Ыa, he was greatly pleased. The friar says: “This is the real and principal cause why the king, during the whole time of my residence in Malabar, behaved to me with so much kindness”. The Maharaja asked him to explain the parts of speech of the English grammar, and on his doing so, went the length of calling him his Guru. He also insisted on his subordinates studying the Dutch language, because of the necessity they had for frequent correspondence with the Netherland East India Company.

Great as was the reputation of Maharaja R─Бma Varma as a ruler, even greater was the fame that he acquired as a patron of arts. To his court flocked from far and near votaries of fine arts of every description and he gave them generous encouragement and support. The description contained in the following verses of the introductory portion of B─Бlar─Бmabharata, is by no means exaggerated:

Pantalam Subrahmanya ┼Ъastri was the profoundest Sanskrit scholar of his age in Kerala. He was the first from the Malabar coast to proceed to Benares, study at first handthe Sabdendu┼Ыekhara of N─Бge┼Ыabhaс╣нс╣нa, and bring that work to the notice of local scholars. Although no works of his have been discovered so far, some of his stray verses are extant. The following is one of them and it was sent to the Maharaja on his health being enquired after by the latter:

Among others who found shelter in Travancore from the Tiger of Mysore was Manorama Tampur─Бс╣нс╣нi of the Zamorin’s family. She was the most learned woman ofher age in Kerala. It may even be added that, great as the culture of women is in Kerala, no lady has risen to her level in Sanskrit scholarship either before or after. The tradition is that, even before she was twelve years of age, she could recite and explain the whole of Bahс╣нс╣нoji D─лksita’s Praudhamanorama. Manorama Tampur─Бс╣нс╣нi, on her arrival in Travancore, was accommodated at Kunnattur and subsequently at Ennakkad, and treated as a royal guest. Much epistolatory literature passed between the Maharaja and her, and the following verses furnish a specimen thereof:

Throughout the reign of R─Бmavarma, not only poets, but all persons who devoted their life to fine arts, received munificent gifts from him.

The Maharaja was also a poet of distinction. In Malavalam he is the author of six Kathakaс╕╖is,viz.,R─Бjas┼лyam, Subh─Бdr─Бharaс╣Зam, Bakavadham, G─Бndh─Бrvavijayam, P─Бnc─Бl─лsvayamvaram, and Kaly─Бaс╣Зsaugandhikam, all based on episodes in the Mah─Бbh─Бrata. While a seventh Kathakali Narak─Бsuravadham, based on a story in the ┼Ъr─лmad Bh─Бgavata, was in processs of composition, A┼Ыvati Tirun─Бl, his grandnephew, meddled with it to its distinct advantage, and the Maharaja thereupon allowed him to complete it. B─Бlar─Бmabharata is the only Sanskrit work of the Maharaja hitherto known.

Being a work on N─Бtya┼Ы─Бstra, B─Бlar─Бmabharata properly opens, with invocatory verses to Unnata-Nс╣Эtta Vin─Бyaka, Naс╣нar─Бja, P─Бrvati in a dancing posture, and ┼Ъr─лpadman─Бbha who appeared as a dancing child before Div─Бkarasany─Бsin. Reference is also made to the Maharaja’s remote ancestors, Cheram─Бnperum─Бс╕╖ N─Бyan─Бr, one of the sixty three Saivite saints (verses 15 and 15), and Kula┼Ыekhara-Azhvar, one of the 12 Vaishanavite Saints (verses 18 and 19), of South India. The former is the author of ─Аtiul─Б, Ponvaс╣Зс╣Зattant─Бtiand Mummaс╣Зikkovai in Tamil, and the latter, of Perumal Tirumozhi in Tamil and Mukundam─Бl─Б in Sanskrit, all devotional poems of superior merit. Balam─Бrtaс╣Зс╕Нa Varma, mentioned in verse 23, has already been referred to by me, as also Rama VarmaтАЩs grand-nephew A┼Ыvati Tirun─Бl. Ravi Varma, the younger brother of Rama Var─▒na, referred to in verse 24, was Makayiram Tirun─Бl, whose unrivalled feats in magic and jugglery excited the admiration of his contemporaries. He died in 1786 A. D. Who the Maharaja’s spiritual preceptor was, is not certain; but in the introductory verses to his R─Бjas┼лyamhe invokes the blessing of a Raghun─Бthas┼лri in the following terms:тАФ

рдЬреНрдЮрд╛рдиреЗ рд╣рд┐ рдпреЗрди рд╕рджреГрд╢реЛ рдирд╣рд┐ рд╢рд╛рд╕реНрддреНрд░рдЬрдиреНрдпреЗ
рдорд╛рдиреНрдпрд╛ рд╕реБрдзрд╛рд╢рдирдЧреБрд░реЛрд░рд┐рд╡ рдпрд╕реНрдп рдХреАрд░реНрддрд┐рдГред
рдЧреЛрддреНрд░рд╛рд╕реБрдзрд╛рд╢рдирдордгрд┐рдВ рдЧреБрд░реБрдорд╕реНрдорджреАрдпрдВ
рдмрдиреНрджреЗ рд╕рджрд╛ рдЧреБрдгрдирд┐рдзрд┐рдВ рд░рдШреБрдирд╛рдерд╕реВрд░рд┐рдореНрее

The same Raghun─Бthas┼лri is referred to in respectful terms by A┼Ыvati Tirun─Бl, who, in his ┼Ъс╣Ыс╣Еg─Бrasudh─Бkara describes himself as тАЬрд╢реНрд░реАрдорджреНрд░рдШреБрдирд╛рде рд╕реБрддреАрд░реНрдерд╛рднрд┐рд╡рд╛рджрдирдЬрд╛рдЧрд░реВрдХреЗрдгтАЭ. It is possible that he might have instructed the Maharaja in Yoga. In any case there can be no doubt that he was both рдпреЛрдЧрдорд╛рд░реНрдЧрдкреНрд░рд╡реАрдг and рдЖрддреНрдорд╡рд┐рджреНрдпрд╛рдкреНрд░рд╡реАрдг as expressly mentioned by himself in verses 28 and 30 respectively.

The only three Indian sovereigns with whom the author of B─Бlar─Бmabharata is, in my opinion, worthy of comparison are King Harsha of Kanouj, King Bhoja of Dhar, and King Krishnadevaraya of Vijayanagar. The name of Maharaja K─Бrtika Tirun─Бl is even to-day remembered with gratitude, affection and respect throughout the length and breadth of Kerala, as the saviour of Kerala from the Tiger of Mysore. bizhavan (cld) Raja, Dharmar─Бja, R─Бmaraja, and Valia Amm─Бvan (the great uncle), are some of the several names by which he is known to posterity. Good cause, indeed, has Travancore, to be proud of this sovereign who strenuously lived the life of an ideal Hindu king and who well and truely laid the foundation of her future peace and prosperityтАЭ

The author is thus portrayed by me in my Citr─Б─Бbhyudaya K─Бvya:тАФ

рдЖрдкрд╛рджрдордзреБрд░реЗ рд╡рд╕реНрддреБрдиреНрдпрдкрд┐ рдмрд╛рд▓реЛрдЪрдирд╛рдореГрддреЗред

The edition of the work is based on a single manuscript belonging to the Palace Library of His Highness the Maha raja. It is written in Malayalam characters and appears to be a century and a half old. Only one manuscript is available of this work and that manuscript was preserved in the Palace Library and it gives me immense pleasure to place this precious work before the learned public.

тАШрднрд╛рд╡рд░рд╕рд╛рд░реНрдердХреНрд░рд┐рдпрд╛рдХрд╛рд░рд┐рддреНрд╡рдВ рднрд░рддрддреНрд╡рдореНтАЩ рдЗрддрд┐ рдирд┐рд╖реНрдХреГрд╖реНрдЯрдВ рднрд░рддрд▓рдХреНрд╖рдгрдореБрдХреНрддреНрд╡рд╛ рддрдЪреНрдЪ рдЕрдЩреНрдЧреЗрд╖реБ рд╢рд┐рд░рдГрдкреНрд░рднреГрддрд┐рд╖реВрдкрд╛рдЩреНрдЧреЗрд╖реБрдирдпрдирд╛рджрд┐рд╖реБ рдкреНрд░рддреНрдпрдЩреНрдЧреЗрд╖реБ рдЧреНрд░реАрд╡рд╛рджрд┐рд╖реБ рдЪ рд╕рдЩреНрдЧрдордпреНрдп рд░рд╛рдЧрддрд╛рд▓рд╛рджрд┐ рдЪ рдмрд╛рд╣реНрдпрдордЩреНрдЧрдВ рднрд╛рд╡рд╛рджреНрдпрднрд┐рд╡реНрдпрдЮреНрдЬрдиреМрдкрдпрд┐рдХрдорднреНрдпреБрдкреЗрддреНрдп рд╡рд┐рд╢рд┐рд╖реНрдпрд╛рднреНрдпрдиреНрддрд░рд╛рдгрд╛рдордЩреНрдЧреЛрдкрд╛рдЩреНрдЧрдкреНрд░рддреНрдпрдЩреНрдЧрд╛рдирд╛рдВ рд╢рд╛рдмреНрджрд┐рдХрд╛рдирд╛рдорд╛рд░реНрдерд┐рдХрд╛рдирд╛рдВ рдЪ рдпрд╛рд╡рддреНрд╕рдореНрднрд╡рдВ рднрд░рддреЛрдкрдпреЛрдЧреАрдирд┐ рд▓рдХреНрд╖рдгрд╛рдирд┐ рд╡рд┐рдирд┐рдпреЛрдЧрд╛рд╢реНрдЪ рд╡рд┐рд╕реНрддрд░рд╢рдГ рдХрдерд┐рддрд╛рдирд┐ред рд╕реБрддрд░рд╛рдореЗрддреЗрд╖реБ рдХреЗрд░рд▓реЗрд╖реБ рдкреНрд░рд╕рд┐рджреНрдзрд╛рд╕реНрддрд╛рд╕реНрддрд╛ рдЖрдЩреНрдЧрд┐рдХрд╕рд╛рддреНрддреНрд╡рд┐рдХрд╛рджреНрдпрд╛ рдЖрднрд┐рдирдпрд┐рдХреНрдпреЛ рдЧрддрдпрд╕реНрддрд╛рджрд╛рддреНрддреНрд╡рд┐рдХрдкреНрд░рдпреЛрдЧрдкрджрд╡реАрдВ рдкреНрд░рддрд┐рдкрдиреНрдирд╛рд╢реНрдЪреЛрджрд╛рджрд╛рд░рд┐рд╖рддред рддрдЪреНрдЪреЗрджрдВ рддрддреНрддреНрд╡рдВ рддрддреНрд░рддрддреНрд░ рд╕рдиреНрджрд░реНрднреЗрд╖реБ рдЧреНрд░рдиреНрдердХрд╛рд░рдореБрджреНрд░рд╛рдЪрд╛рдХреНрдпреИ : рд╕реНрд╡рдЪрд┐рдиреНрддрд┐рддрд╛рднрд┐рдирдпрдкреНрд░рд╕реНрддрд╛рд╡рд╛рддреН рдкреНрд░рдХрдЯрдорд╡рдЧрдореНрдпрддреЗред рдпрдерд╛тАФ
